@article{17091852919260101,
 abstract  = "Cholesterol irradiated by a quartz mercury vapour lamp (K.B.B. atmospheric type, 220 volts) for one hour at a distance of 1 foot was dissolved in linseed oil so as to make a 3 p.c. solution. After a probationary period of one month in hospital, a boy of three years with severe rickets was given this solution of cholesterol, with striking results, the rickets having completely healed after four months, where previous treatment with cod-liver oil had been a failure. The inorganic phosphorus rose from 4-67 to 6.8 mgm. per 100 c.c. of plasma, and the blood calcium rose from 7.15 to 10.4 mgm. per 100 c.c. of serum. Irradiated cholestrol, when kept for some time, loses its antirachitic power; prolonged exposure to the ultra-violet rays will also render it inactive again. - D. B. STEABBEN (London). (PhA,12:2,101, No. 587)",
